{
  "text": "The use of topical retinol to improve cellulite was proposed by Kligman et al ., [CITATION_1] based on the capacity of all-trans-retinoic acid (tretinoin) to promote the synthesis of glycosaminoglycans in normal skin and increase the deposition of collagen in the photodamaged dermis. Hypothetically, these effects could lead to an increase of the thickness and firmness of the dermis, putting a 'cap' over the more mobile fat which can easily change its shape without any change in volume. The proposal of retinol instead of tretinoin was based on the better tolerability and the evidence that retinol is metabolized to retinoic acid in the skin. Twenty patients were included in an intraindividual controlled preliminary study. Retinol 0.3% or its vehicle was applied to opposite lateral thighs twice daily for 6 months and the patients were evaluated clinically by the investigator, and by laser Doppler velocimetry. Nineteen patients completed the study. In the instrumental evaluation the retinol-treated thigh showed better results than the vehicletreated thigh (in spite of the large variance), in 12 patients the clinical improvement was higher with retinol than with vehicle and in seven patients there was no difference between the retinol side and the vehicle side. Despite the fact that there was a statistically significant difference in the retinol-treated thighs, the small number of patients included does not allow the extrapolation of results and more studies are required to confirm this treatment option.",
  "citation_candidates": [
